President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring April 18 to April 24, 2010, as National Volunteer Week in the United States. In the proclamation, he highlights the importance of volunteers in the country's history and encourages more Americans, especially young people, to engage in volunteer work. He mentions the various ways volunteers contribute, such as mentoring students, feeding the homeless, and rebuilding after natural disasters. The president emphasizes the need for a renewed commitment to service in order to address the challenges faced by the nation. He mentions initiatives like United We Serve and the Edward M. Kennedy Serve America Act that aim to promote and expand volunteerism. The proclamation concludes by calling upon all Americans to observe National Volunteer Week by participating in service projects and making service a part of their daily lives.